      <div class="homeostatic-heading">HOMEOSTATIC</div>
      <br/>
      In order to understand how the brain coordinates feeding behavior, it is necessary
      to identify the key players and brain regions involved. The key players acting
      in the brain to regulate hunger may be neuropeptides or hormones made within the
      brain, or they may be made in the peripheral organs (e.g. pancreas, gut, liver, etc).
      We are particularly interested in the roles of melanin-concentrating hormone (MCH),
      which is made exclusively with the brain; ghrelin, a gut peptide; and fibroblast
      growth factor 21 (FGF21), which is primarily released by the liver, pancreas, and fat cells.
