      <div class="nutrition-heading">NUTRITION</div>
      <br/>
      <em>We are what we eat.</em> More than just feeding our bodies, nutrients like fats, sugars, and protein,
      have also have a significant impact on brain neurochemistry. We are particularly
      interested in the role of fructose on the neurobiology of obesity. Fructose
      is a simple sugar that tastes sweeter than glucose and bonds with glucose
      to make table sugar. We consume fructose in excess by consuming soda and juices,
      packaged goods, baked goods, and even dairy products that contain added sugars.
      It has been linked to the development of obesity and Type II diabetes thus research
      in our lab will test if fructose-rich diets promote neuroplasticity leading to
      diet-induced obesity. We compare the healthy and unhealthy brain to learn and
      prevent diet-mediated maladaptations that tip the body weight scale.
